Installing Syslack Linux Is Extremely Hard TO Install Unless if You use Ubuntu Server install

1 Download Ubuntu Server Iso From https://ubuntu.com/download/server
2 Flash Iso Using BalenaEtcher Rufus dd mode Or Ventoy
3 Boot from an Ubuntu Server ISO or a debootstrap‑based live environment.
  Switch to tty2 (Ctrl+Alt+F2) Then run sudo passwd root then set your root password
4 Run Root using su -
4 Locales and Mirrors
  Generate locales manually:
  dpkg-reconfigure locales
5 Edit /etc/apt/sources.list using sudo nano /etc/apt/sources.list to point to Ubuntu mirrors Then
  deb http://archive.ubuntu.com/ubuntu noble main universe multiverse restricted
  deb http://archive.ubuntu.com/ubuntu noble-updates main universe multiverse restricted
  deb http://archive.ubuntu.com/ubuntu noble-security main universe multiverse restricted
6 Disk Configuration (fdisk + ext4 + swap)
  fdisk -l
  Partition manually:

      UEFI setup:

        /dev/sda1 → EFI System Partition (512MB, type EF00, FAT32)

        /dev/sda2 → root (ext4, rest of disk)

        /dev/sda3 → swap (2–4GB depending on RAM)

    Legacy BIOS setup (no Syslinux):

        /dev/sda1 → root (ext4, whole disk minus swap)

        /dev/sda2 → swap


7 Format:
  mkfs.vfat /dev/sda1   # only for UEFI
  mkfs.ext4 /dev/sda2
  mkswap /dev/sda3
  swapon /dev/sda3

  Mount root
  mount /dev/sda2 /mnt
  mkdir /mnt/boot
  mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot   # only if UEFI

8 Base System Install
  Bootstrap Ubuntu into /mnt:
  debootstrap --arch=amd64 noble /mnt http://archive.ubuntu.com/ubuntu/
  Mount pseudo‑filesystems:
  
  mount -t proc /proc /mnt/proc
  mount -t sysfs /sys /mnt/sys
  mount --bind /dev /mnt/dev

  Enter chroot:
  chroot /mnt /bin/bash
9 Installing Bootloader
  Install GRUB
  apt install grub-pc grub-efi-amd64
  Legacy BIOS
  grub-install /dev/sda
  update-grub
  UEFI
  grub-install --target=x86_64-efi --efi-directory=/boot --bootloader-id=Syslack
  update-grub

10 Unified Kernel Images
   apt install linux-image-generic-lts
   Enable unified kernel images (UKI) if desired
   Configure systemd-boot or GRUB with UKI entries in /boot/efi/EFI/Syslack/
11 Identity Rituals
   Set hostname
   echo "yourname" > /etc/hostname

   Create user account:
   adduser yourname
   usermod -aG sudo yourname

   Configure timezone
   dpkg-reconfigure tzdata

   Configure network manually
   Edit /etc/netplan/config.yaml
   netplan apply
12 Finalization
   Update package lists
   apt update && apt upgrade

  Exit chroot and unmount
  exit
  umount -R /mnt
13 Reboot into Syslack Linux.
14 run sudo apt update
15 run sudo nano /etc/default/grub
   (If You Need it) Change
    GRUB_TIMEOUT=0 To GRUB_TIMEOUT=5 Then GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=hidden to GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu
    then Change GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR=`( . /etc/os-release; echo ${NAME:-Ubuntu} ) 2>/dev/null || echo Ubuntu` to GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR=`( . /etc/os-release; echo ${NAME:-Ubuntu} ) 2>/dev/null || echo Syslack Linux`
    Ctrl X Y Enter Then sudo update-grub
16 Run sudo nano /etc/os-release
   Then change PREETY_NAME="Ubuntu 24.04.3 LTS" To PREETY_NAME="Syhttps://github.com/Haikal02-alt/Syslack-Linuxslack Linux"
   Change NAME="Ubuntu" To NAME="Syslack Linux"
   Change VERSION="24.04.3 LTS (Noble Numbat)" To VERSION=""
   Change VERSION_CODENAME=noble To VERSION_CODENAME=
   Why Version And Version Codename Must be Blank It Because Its Rolling Release Distro
   Change ID=ubuntu to ID=syslack
   Change HOME_URL="https://ubuntu.com/" To HOME_URL="https://github.com/Haikal02-alt/Syslack-Linux"
   Then Reboot
17 Change Some Ubuntu To Syslack On /etc/issue on sudo nano /etc/issue If You See Ubuntu 24.04.3 LTS \n \1 Change it To Syslack Linux \n \1
   Also run sudo nano /etc/issue.net Then Change Ubuntu 24.04.3 LTS To Syslack Linux
   Then Reboot Again sudo reboot
18 Adjust GRUB Scripts
   Run sudo nano /etc/grub.d/10_linux
   If You See if [ "x${GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR}" = "x" ] ; then
   OS=GNU/Linux
   And OS="${GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR} GNU/Linux" 
   Change it To
   if [ "x${GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR}" = "x" ] ; then
   OS=
   And
   OS="${GRUB_DISTRIBUTOR}"
   Then Find GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU
   Then Disable GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU By Changing GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU="true" to GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU="false"
   Then sudo update-grub
   Then Reboot Again using sudo reboot

19 Have Fun And Start Using Syslack Linux Which You Can Say I Use Syslack BTW
